      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20
Elon Musk is the richest person in the world, and an active Twitter user. W=
hen he tweets, he gets a lot of spammy replies, many of which seem to be wr=
itten by automated bots. He has complained about this a lot. Eventually he =
decided to do something about it. The thing that he decided to do about it =
was=C2=A0buy Twitter. On April 13, he sent a letter to Twitter Inc.=E2=80=
=99s board of directors offering to buy the company for $54.20 per share in=
 cash. =E2=80=9CIf our twitter bid succeeds,=E2=80=9D he tweeted,=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Cwe will defeat the spam bots or die trying!=E2=80=9DHis Twitter bid s=
ucceeded. On April 25, Twitter and Musk issued a joint press release announ=
cing that he had agreed to buy Twitter for $54.20 per share. The press rele=
ase included a quote from Musk promising to =E2=80=9Cmake Twitter better=E2=
=80=9D by, among other things, =E2=80=9Cdefeating the spam bots.=E2=80=9D H=
e was really mad at the spam bots! He wanted to buy Twitter because of the =
spam bots.Yesterday he announced that he does not want to buy Twitter=C2=A0=
because of the spam bots:Elon Musk declared he won=E2=80=99t proceed with h=
is $44 billion takeover of Twitter Inc. unless the social media giant can p=
rove bots make up fewer than 5% of its users, casting yet more uncertainty =
over the deal.The billionaire tweeted =E2=80=9Cthis deal cannot move forwar=
d=E2=80=9D unless Twitter provides proof of its claims, reiterating his own=
 view that the ratio is far higher. =E2=80=A6Twitter said it is =E2=80=9Cco=
mmitted to completing the transaction on the agreed price and terms as prom=
ptly as practicable,=E2=80=9D in a statement on Tuesday. =E2=80=A6The battl=
e over bots has become a sticking point for Musk, who told a tech conferenc=
e in Miami on Monday that fake users make up at least 20% of all Twitter ac=
counts, possibly as high as 90%. Twitter regularly states in its quarterly =
results that the average of false or spam accounts =E2=80=9Crepresented few=
er than 5% of our monthly daily active users during the quarter,=E2=80=9D a=
dding that it applied =E2=80=9Csignificant judgment=E2=80=9D to its estimat=
e, and the true number could be higher.I think it is important to be clear =
here that=C2=A0Musk is lying. The spam bots are not why he is backing away =
from the deal, as you can tell from the fact that the spam bots are why he=
=C2=A0did=C2=A0the deal.=C2=A0He has produced no evidence at all that Twitt=
er=E2=80=99s estimates are wrong, and certainly not that they are materiall=
y wrong or made=C2=A0in bad faith. (Musk can only get out of the deal if Tw=
itter's filings are wrong  in a way that would cause a =E2=80=9Cmaterial ad=
verse effect=E2=80=9D on Twitter, which is vanishingly unlikely.) His own s=
upposed methodology for counting spam bots is laughable. Yesterday Twitter=
=E2=80=99s chief executive officer, Parag Agrawal,  tweeted a thread explai=
ning in general terms=C2=A0how Twitter estimates that fake accounts represe=
nt fewer than 5% of its count of active users, and how this analysis can=E2=
=80=99t be easily replicated by outsiders (because they don=E2=80=99t know =
which accounts are real, and also because they don=E2=80=99t know which acc=
ounts Twitter  counts as daily active users). It seems clear that Agrawal=
=E2=80=99s thoughtful answer is basically correct.[1] Musk responded with a=
  poop emoji.More important, nothing has=C2=A0changed=C2=A0about the bot pr=
oblem since Musk signed the merger agreement.=C2=A0Twitter has   published =
the same qualified estimate =E2=80=94=C2=A0that fewer than 5% of monetizabl=
e accounts are fake =E2=80=94=C2=A0for the last=C2=A0eight years.=C2=A0Musk=
 knew those estimates, and declined to do any nonpublic due diligence befor=
e signing the merger agreement. He knew about the spam bot problem before s=
igning the merger agreement, as we know=C2=A0because he talked about it con=
stantly, including while announcing the merger agreement.=C2=A0If he didn=
=E2=80=99t want to buy Twitter because there are spam bots, he should not h=
ave signed a contract to buy Twitter. No new information has come to light =
about spam bots in the last three weeks.=C2=A0What has=C2=A0happened in the=
 last three weeks? Well, the prices of tech stocks have=C2=A0gone down, mak=
ing the $54.20 price that Musk agreed to look a bit rich. (Snap Inc.,=C2=A0=
a social-media competitor to Twitter, is down more than 30% since Musk made=
 his offer on April 13.) And the price of Tesla Inc. stock, which he is rel=
ying on to finance part of the purchase price, has also gone down, making h=
im poorer and making the $54.20 price look even more expensive. (Tesla is=
=C2=A0down almost 30% since he made his offer.)=C2=A0So he is angling to re=
price the deal for straightforward market reasons. But that is very clearly=
 not allowed by the merger agreement that he signed: Public-company merger =
agreements allocate broad market risk to the buyer, and he can=E2=80=99t ge=
t out just because stocks went down.So he is pretending that he wants to re=
price the deal for other reasons. He is not pretending very hard =E2=80=94 =
the poop emoji is not going to hold up in court! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but he=E2=
=80=99s doing enough to confuse the public=C2=A0and give his fans a pretext=
 to believe that he is really the victim here.Poor Twitter. After Musk anno=
unced that he had taken=C2=A0a 9% stake in Twitter, but before he offered t=
o buy the company, he  signed a standstill agreement under which he would j=
oin Twitter board=E2=80=99s board of directors and promise=C2=A0not to buy =
more than 14.9% of the stock. Four days later he  tore up that agreement; t=
hen he made his bid. I wrote at the time:This is an awkward situation for T=
witter's board. They can=E2=80=99t really accept Musk's offer. For one thin=
g the price is embarrassingly low; again, Twitter traded above the offer pr=
ice last October. For another thing, the financing seems to be made up of c=
obwebs and phlogiston. But also Musk has joked about taking companies priva=
te before, and he generally changes his mind a lot. (He agreed to join Twit=
ter=E2=80=99s board last week! And then changed his mind four days later!) =
If you are a well-advised professional public company board, it is just cat=
astrophic to imagine that you might say =E2=80=9Cokay Elon $54.20 it is=E2=
=80=9D and then he=E2=80=99d say =E2=80=9Cha no I was kidding, psych!=E2=80=
