=99s estimates are not only correct, but probably conservative. =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0It seems very reasonable to assume that there remain lots of Twitter =
users who consume tweets, or even like them, but never send a public tweet.=
 Moreover, it also seems likely that bot accounts are more likely to send p=
ublic tweets =E2=80=94 that=E2=80=99s kind of the point! In other words, Sp=
arkToro and Followerwonk=E2=80=99s methodology, which defines an active use=
r as someone who sent a public tweet in the last 90 days, likely over-sampl=
ed bot accounts even as it completely ignored lurkers.=E2=80=9D[2] One pote=
ntial answer is =E2=80=9Ca $10 billion reverse termination fee=E2=80=9D but=
 what are the odds he=E2=80=99ll agree to that?[3]=C2=A0The debt financing=
=C2=A0should=C2=A0be available =E2=80=94=C2=A0the financing comes from big =
banks, there is no market out, and the conditions to the financing will pro=
bably be met =E2=80=94 but you could imagine the banks trying to back out. =
For one thing, the financing is risky; the banks have committed to fund $13=
 billion of debt at Twitter, roughly=C2=A0eight times Twitter=E2=80=99s exp=
ected 2022=C2=A0earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortizat=
ion. For another thing, it=E2=80=99s even riskier to fund that much debt on=
=C2=A0a company whose owner doesn=E2=80=99t want it; lending 8x EBITDA to E=
lon Musk=E2=80=99s favorite toy is a good trade, but lending 8x EBITDA to h=
is abandoned toy is not. And Musk is the banks=E2=80=99 client, not Twitter=
; they want to stay in his good graces by doing what he wants. A month ago,=
 that meant committing=C2=A0to lend Twitter $13 billion. Now it might mean =
saying =E2=80=9Coh no we could never lend Twitter $13 billion, who told you=
 that?=E2=80=9D That said, the banks have some important long-term reasons =
to stick to their commitments. Their commitment letters =E2=80=94=C2=A0prom=
ises from big banks to fund the purchase =E2=80=94=C2=A0are what got the de=
al done, and they are important in many other deals. Private equity firms b=
uy companies all the time by saying =E2=80=9Cwe are good for the money, her=
e are our=C2=A0commitment letters from banks, they=E2=80=99re basically as =
good as money.=E2=80=9D If commitment letters are worthless then mergers wi=
ll be harder to do; it is good for the banks to have a reputation for stick=
ing to their word. But it is also good for the banks to have a reputation f=
or helping their clients.=C2=A0[4] This point was made on Twitter by law pr=
ofessors Morgan Ricks (=E2=80=9CMusk's contempt or disregard for laws / nor=
ms / prosocial behavior makes judges *less* likely to issue specific perfor=
mance order against him.=C2=A0What happens when he blows the order off? You=
're going to issue a contempt order and what, fine him? Have him arrested i=
n Texas?=E2=80=9D) and Dave Hoffman (=E2=80=9CI=C2=A0think that ordering a =
*board* of respectable law abiding citizens to complete a transaction (IBP)=
 is one thing.=C2=A0Ordering a ...whatever he is...to do it is another.=E2=
=80=9D).
