 solid; background-color: #ccc;">this level of precision</a>:</p><blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On March 1, 2018, Defendants received the mo=
nth-end February 2018 IDS Risk Report for Structured Alpha. On March 5, 201=
8, Bond-Nelson forwarded a manipulated version of that report to AGI US=E2=
=80=99s Structured Alpha Product Specialists for dissemination to investors=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Specifically, for the AllianzGI Structure=
d Alpha 1000 LLC fund, in one instance, Bond-Nelson materially reduced loss=
es in a stress scenario from -22.0557450847078% to=C2=A0-12.0557450847078%.=
</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What. If you had invested=C2=
=A0<em>one trillion dollars=C2=A0</em>in that fund, in the hypothetical=C2=
=A0stress scenario you would lose $220,557,450,847.078, according to the =
=E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D calculation. =E2=80=9CBummer,=E2=80=9D you would say=
; =E2=80=9CI can=E2=80=99t believe I lost two hundred twenty billion, five =
hundred fifty-seven million, four hundred fifty thousand, eight hundred for=
ty-seven dollars and seven and four-fifths cents. I had big plans for that =
four-fifths of a penny!=E2=80=9D But the fund=E2=80=99s managers nefariousl=
y sent you a risk report saying that in that stress scenario you would only=
 lose=C2=A012.0557450847078% of your money, and not the more accurate=C2=A0=
22.0557450847078% reported by their true stress tests.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Of course it is illegal to change that first digit but, I am so=
rry,=C2=A0I am so hung up on why they included all the other ones. Why didn=
=E2=80=99t they round? Oh, I mean, I know why. If you send someone a number=
 with that many digits they figure you must have done Some Real Math to get=
 it. =E2=80=9CLook how many digits this number has,=E2=80=9D they say, =E2=
=80=9Cwhat are the odds that the first one is made up?=E2=80=9D</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway. That is from a US Securities and Exchange Comm=
ission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27745071.25=
9617/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi04NA/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB252a440e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">enforcement action</a> against Allianz =
Global Investors US LLC and three of its former portfolio managers, Gregoir=
e Tournant, Trevor Taylor and Stephen Bond-Nelson; there is a parallel <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27745071.259617/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTcvYWxsaWFuei1nb=
G9iYWwtZXgtaW52ZXN0bWVudC1vZmZpY2VyLXRvdXJuYW50LWNoYXJnZWQtd2l0aC1mcmF1ZD9j=
bXBpZD1CQkQwNTE3MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV=
3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA1MTcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB02350b4d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> federal criminal action</a>, and AGI, Tay=
lor and Bond-Nelson have agreed to plead guilty.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">AGI offered a series of funds in a strategy called =E2=80=9CStructure=
d Alpha=E2=80=9D; each=C2=A0fund offered investors (1) exposure to some ind=
ex of stocks or bonds, (2) some additional yield-enhancement (covered-call =
selling, etc.) and hedging (put buying, etc.) strategies, (3) high fees and=
 (4) excitingly pseudo-mathematical monthly reports to make the customers f=
eel good about how seriously AGI was managing their money. The basic idea i=
s that investors get exposure to the index, maybe do a bit better than the =
index in good times, and are protected from crashes in bad times. In return=
 they pay the high fees. And getting the reports in the good times reassure=
s them that they will be protected in the bad times.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">The allegation=C2=A0from the SEC and Justice Department is that t=
he reports, and the downside protection, were mostly fake. For instance, th=
e hedging strategies <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/27745071.259617/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMv=
MjAyMi9jb21wLXByMjAyMi04NC5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCd22f3314" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
were advertised</a> as buying puts that were 10% to 25% out of the money:</=
p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For example, in a pitch book sli=
de for Structured Alpha that Tournant showed to investors repeatedly from a=
t least November 2016 through March 2020, Tournant and AGI US represented t=
hat hedging positions included put options that were =E2=80=9Claddered for =
various market outcomes to the downside=E2=80=9D with =E2=80=9C<em>[s]trike=
 distances from -10% to -25%.</em>=E2=80=9D (Emphasis added.) The slide exp=
lained that =E2=80=9C[t]he primary objective of the hedging positions is to=
 protect the strategy from a short-term equity market crash,=E2=80=9D which=
 was =E2=80=9C[d]efined as a decline of 10% to 15% in less than 5 days.=E2=
=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in fact, =E2=80=9Cb=
eginning around February 2018, strike prices averaged from -30% to -50%=E2=
=80=9D out of the money, whoops.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or there w=
ere all those risk reports, which included option sensitivities, stress-tes=
ts, etc., often to a comical degree of precision, which the AGI managers th=
en fudged arbitrarily. I quoted the one above, changing -22.whatever to -12=
.whatever. Here=E2=80=99s another good one:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Bond-Nelson altered the outputs of stress test scenarios for t=
he AllianzGI Structured Alpha 1000 LLC fund: one entry from -24.59873893957=
98% to -12.2993694697899% and another from -30.8197078741882% to -15.409853=
9370941%. These altered amounts were exactly one-half of the actual IDS str=
ess test outputs and had no basis in fact.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Changing the first 2 to a 1, I get, that's easy. Dividing in h=
alf is hilarious; like, did his calculator have that many digits?=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They also allegedly sent prospective investors=
 altered reports of=C2=A0<em>actual=C2=A0</em>historical daily returns, =E2=
=80=9Csmoothing=E2=80=9D them to report smaller gains and losses each day, =
which =E2=80=9Cconcealed from investors the true downside risk and volatili=
ty of Structured Alpha.=E2=80=9D And they allegedly=C2=A0faked =E2=80=9Catt=
ribution spreadsheets=E2=80=9D that calculated how much of the fund=E2=80=
=99s return was due to different parts of its strategy. (In particular, the=
y altered the spreadsheets to make it seem like they spent more on hedging =
than they actually did.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or there is this s=
trategy for producing =E2=80=9CEV sheets,=E2=80=9D spreadsheets that were s=
ent to prospective investors calculating expected values of the portfolio i=
n different market conditions:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Tournant created a spreadsheet that showed actual EV data for the AllianzGI=
 Structured Alpha 1000 LLC fund. Tournant then manipulated the data to mate=
rially increase the gains and decrease the losses, making the data material=
ly false and misleading. Specifically, Tournant multiplied the gains by 1.4=
 (increasing the gains), and the losses by .25 (reducing the losses). He th=
en emailed the altered spreadsheet to another AGI US employee for use in th=
e investor meeting. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Manipulation =
of EV sheets was labor-intensive. So, on August 5, 2017, Taylor emailed Tou=
rnant password-protected, step-by-step instructions on how to alter data an=
d avoid detection by investors. Among other things, the instructions specif=
ied: =E2=80=9C3) On a blank sheet in the workbook, copy and past the ENTIRE=
 EV SHEET THEREBY DUPLICATING IT EXACTLY.=E2=80=9D Then, after copying the =
data from the actual EV Sheet, the instructions specified to create new man=
ipulated figures: =E2=80=9C7) On the new sheet target appropriate EV=E2=80=
=99s and simply apply the formulas you desire and copy up or down.=E2=80=9D=
 The =E2=80=9Cformulas=E2=80=9D created falsified numbers by multiplying am=
ounts on the actual EV sheets to reduce the magnitude of expected losses. =
=E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Taylor=E2=80=99s instructions als=
o discussed concealing from investors the formulas showing altered EV outpu=
ts: =E2=80=9C<em>During a presentation, I would not put the mouse over any =
cells that are populated thereby showing its formula unless [you] did a cop=
y paste special value.</em>=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">It goes on and on like this. From 2016 through 2019, Tournant and Ta=
ylor each got paid at least $10 million a year doing this stuff. Then they =
lost roughly half their investors=E2=80=99 money =E2=80=94=C2=A0more than $=
5 billion =E2=80=94=C2=A0in a blink in March 2020 during Covid-related vola=
tility. Oops! =E2=80=9CThe 2020 COVID-related market volatility revealed th=
at AGI US and the defendants had misled investors about the fund=E2=80=99s =
level of risk,=E2=80=9D says the SEC.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The b=
asic idea here is that in a broadly rising stock market, your performance w=
ill be good if you just buy the index. Your performance will be even better=
 if you double down on that bet, selling puts, selling volatility, etc. You=
r performance will be worse=C2=A0if you spend a lot of money on hedging dow=
nside risk.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Your clients will like good per=
formance, but they=C2=A0will also like to be=C2=A0<em>told=C2=A0</em>that y=
ou have hedged your downside risk.=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s easy for <em>them</em>=
 to just buy the index; it=E2=80=99s hard for them to get index performance=
 in good times=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>protect themselves from crashes. If y=
ou offer them a product that does as well as the index as stocks go up, and=
 protects them if stocks go down, they will be happy and pay you big fees. =
This is a hard product to make, but it is an easy product to fake,=C2=A0<em=
>as long as stocks keep going up.=C2=A0</em>Just buy the index, watch stock=
s go up, lie about buying puts, and send investors reports saying =E2=80=9C=
look how hedged we are, if the market crashes you will only lose=C2=A012.05=
57450847078%!=E2=80=9D They will never notice, until the market crashes and=
 they lose 48.2229803388312%. Then they know you were lying.</p><table clas=
