have committed to fund $13 billion of debt at Twitter, roughly=C2=A0eight t=
imes Twitter=E2=80=99s expected 2022=C2=A0earnings before interest, taxes, =
depreciation and amortization. For another thing, it=E2=80=99s even riskier=
 to fund that much debt on=C2=A0a company whose owner doesn=E2=80=99t want =
it; lending 8x EBITDA to Elon Musk=E2=80=99s favorite toy is a good trade, =
but lending 8x EBITDA to his abandoned toy is not. And Musk is the banks=E2=
=80=99 client, not Twitter; they want to stay in his good graces by doing w=
hat he wants. A month ago, that meant committing=C2=A0to lend Twitter $13 b=
illion. Now it might mean saying =E2=80=9Coh no we could never lend Twitter=
 $13 billion, who told you that?=E2=80=9D That said, the banks have some im=
portant long-term reasons to stick to their commitments. Their commitment l=
etters =E2=80=94=C2=A0promises from big banks to fund the purchase =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0are what got the deal done, and they are important in many other d=
